(* 27 — the mutant.  The lambda is unchanged; the call breaks its contract.

   THIS IS THE NINTH FALSE PROOF, IN ONE FILE.  `g`'s parameter is `{v | v != 0}`, and its
   body proves `100 / k` from that.  The call then passes ZERO.  Under the old checker the
   lambda's type was `ROpaque()` — it carried no parameter contract — so the application
   discharged nothing, and the verdict was the body's obligation alone:

       ok: 1 obligation(s) proved          exit 0

   ...and then, at run time, ZeroDivisionError.  One obligation proved is not "the program
   is safe".  It is "the body is safe IF the parameter is non-zero" — a promise the call
   was never asked to keep.  It is 22 one step along: 22 made `synth` LOOK at the body;
   this makes the call PAY for what the body assumed.

   Now: two obligations, one unproved.  The body still proves `k != 0` (it may assume its
   parameter), and the call `g(x - x)` owes `0 != 0`, which is false. *)

module LambdaPreUnsafe

fn use(x : Int) : Int =
  let g = fn (k : {v : Int | v != 0}) => 100 / k in
  g(x - x)                          (* g(0).  The divisor is zero, and always was. *)

fn main(io : IO) : IO =
  print(io, int_to_string(use(7)))
